vulnerabilities.description:
> The header for "Accept-Language", when parsed by negotiator is vulnerable to Regular Expression Denial of Service via a specially crafted string.
> 
> -- [nodesecurity.io](https://nodesecurity.io/advisories/106)

> If the node process makes a request with a multipart attachment, and the type of the body option is a Number, then that many bytes of uninitialized memory will be sent in the body of the request. 
> 
> -- [github.com](https://github.com/request/request/pull/2018)
This vulnerability could cause the unintentional leakage of bearer tokens.

The CLI in npm before 2.15.1 and 3.x before 3.8.3, as used in Node.js 0.10 before 0.10.44, 0.12 before 0.12.13, 4 before 4.4.2, and 5 before 5.10.0, includes bearer tokens with arbitrary requests, which allows remote HTTP servers to obtain sensitive information by reading Authorization headers.
Long version strings can result in a regular expression denial of service.
The semver package before 4.3.2 for Node.js allows attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption) via a long version string, aka a "regular expression denial of service (ReDoS)."

> The primary function, minimatch(path, pattern) is vulnerable to ReDoS in the pattern parameter.
> 
> -- [nodesecurity.io](https://nodesecurity.io/advisories/118)
The `node-cli` library makes insecure use of temporary files thus allowing the overwriting of files that the starting-user has permission to modify.
A possible information exposure exists when `number` objects are provided to stringConcat, resulting in uninitialized memory being written to the stream.
There are `relevant security flaws surrounding command injection and unexpected globbing` due to the use of the exec function.
A prototype override protection bypass is possible, which allows attackers to overwrite properties and functions. A previous solution for the problem is incomplete.

Hawk before 3.1.3 and 4.x before 4.1.1 allow remote attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption or partial outage) via a long (1) header or (2) URI that is matched against an improper regular expression.

vulnerabilities.vulnerability_title: [CVE-2015-8860]  Improper Link Resolution Before File Access ("Link Following")
vulnerabilities.description: The tar package before 2.0.0 for Node.js allows remote attackers to write to arbitrary files via a symlink attack in an archive.
The package contain a regular expression that is vulnerable to ReDoS attacks.
Some types of input can result in a Regular Expression Denial of Service (ReDoS)
The uglify-js package before 2.6.0 for Node.js allows attackers to cause a denial of service (CPU consumption) via crafted input in a parse call, aka a "regular expression denial of service (ReDoS)."

> With the sanitize option on it is possible to create a link with a javascript: protocol with the following: [URL](javascript:document;alert(1)).
> 
> -- [github.com](https://github.com/chjj/marked/pull/592)

vulnerabilities.vulnerability_title: Cross Site Scripting (XSS) in data links
vulnerabilities.description: Allowing `data:` links opens this package up to an XSS attack.

vulnerabilities.vulnerability_title: Tmp files readable by other users
vulnerabilities.description:
> Sync-exec uses tmp directories as a buffer before returning values. Other users on the server have read access to the tmp directory, possibly allowing an attacker on the server to obtain confidential information from the buffer/tmp file, while it exists.
> 
> -- [nodesecurity.io](https://nodesecurity.io/advisories/310)
